# Multi-Profile VNC Display (Option A — Virtual Display Per Profile)

Each running profile gets its own isolated virtual display with its own VNC stream. The frontend shows a grid of live VNC tiles.

## User Review Required

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Port range**: The plan exposes Docker ports `6081–6090` for up to 10 concurrent VNC sessions. Adjust if you need more/fewer.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Existing VNC tab**: The current single-VNC "Browser View" tab will be **replaced** by the new multi-profile grid. The old single-viewer behavior is preserved — clicking a tile maximizes it to full view. Confirm this is acceptable.

---

## Proposed Changes

### 1. Python — Display Manager

A new module that allocates/deallocates Xvfb + x11vnc + noVNC instances per profile.

#### [NEW] [display_manager.py](file:///c:/Users/yaros/Downloads/anti/python/browser_control/display_manager.py)

Thread-safe `DisplayManager` class:
- `allocate(profile_name) → { display_num, vnc_port }` — starts Xvfb on `:100+N` at `1366x768x16`, x11vnc on `5901+N`, noVNC proxy on `6081+N`
- `release(profile_name)` — kills all three processes for that profile
- `get_all_sessions() → [{ profile_name, vnc_port, display_num }]` — returns active sessions
- `cleanup_all()` — kills everything on shutdown
- Uses a `Lock` and tracks PIDs in a dict
- Display numbers start at `:100` to avoid conflict with the main `:99`

---

### 2. Python — Wire Display Into Browser Launch

#### [MODIFY] [run_workflow.py](file:///c:/Users/yaros/Downloads/anti/python/getting_started/run_workflow.py)

- Import `DisplayManager`; create a single instance in `WorkflowRunner.__init__`
- In [process_account()](file:///c:/Users/yaros/Downloads/anti/python/getting_started/run_workflow.py#254-390): call `display_mgr.allocate(profile_name)` before browser start, store display_num in `browser_state`
- In [process_account() finally](file:///c:/Users/yaros/Downloads/anti/python/getting_started/run_workflow.py#254-390): call `display_mgr.release(profile_name)`
- Emit new event `display_allocated` with `{ profile, vnc_port, display_num }` so the server knows

#### [MODIFY] [browser_setup.py](file:///c:/Users/yaros/Downloads/anti/python/browser_control/browser_setup.py)

- Add optional `display` parameter to [create_browser_context()](file:///c:/Users/yaros/Downloads/anti/python/browser_control/browser_setup.py#391-570)
- When `display` is provided and running on Linux, set `os.environ["DISPLAY"]` to the given display number **in the current thread** before launching Camoufox (use a threading Lock to safely override/restore the env var)

#### [MODIFY] [worker_utils.py](file:///c:/Users/yaros/Downloads/anti/python/internal_systems/shared_utilities/worker_utils.py)

- Pass through the new `display` parameter to `_create_browser_context()`

---

### 3. Server — API Endpoint for Active Displays

#### [MODIFY] [workflows.ts](file:///c:/Users/yaros/Downloads/anti/server/api/workflows.ts)

- Parse `display_allocated` events from Python stdout (already comes through `__EVENT__` protocol)
- Track active VNC sessions in an in-memory `Map<string, { profileName, vncPort, displayNum }>`
- Clean up entries on `profile_completed` or process exit

#### [NEW] [displays.ts](file:///c:/Users/yaros/Downloads/anti/server/api/displays.ts)

New Express router with one endpoint:
- `GET /api/displays` — returns the list of active `{ profileName, vncPort }` sessions
- Registered in [index.ts](file:///c:/Users/yaros/Downloads/anti/server/index.ts)

#### [MODIFY] [websocket.ts](file:///c:/Users/yaros/Downloads/anti/server/websocket.ts)

- Forward `display_allocated` / `display_released` events as WebSocket broadcasts so the frontend can update the grid in real time

#### [MODIFY] [index.ts](file:///c:/Users/yaros/Downloads/anti/server/index.ts)

- Mount the new `/api/displays` router

